```json
{
  "application": "SLURM",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "git-lfs@2.11.0",
    "account": "sys200",
    "partition": "hotel-gpu",
    "nodes": 1,
    "tasks_per_node": 1,
    "cpus_per_task": 8,
    "time": "01:00:00",
    "scheduler_module": "slurm",
    "spack_version": "0.17.3",
    "spack_instance_name": "gpu",
    "spack_instance_dir": "/cm/shared/apps/spack/0.17.3/gpu",
    "spack_package": "git-lfs@2.11.0",
    "spack_compiler": "gcc@11.2.0",
    "spack_variants": "",
    "spack_dependencies": "",
    "spack_spec": "git-lfs@2.11.0 % gcc@11.2.0 "
  }
}
```

This script is running on a SLURM cluster. It uses the `sbatch` command to submit a job to the SLURM scheduler. 

The script also uses `spack` to install the `git-lfs` package with the specified version and compiler. 

The script includes details about the SLURM configuration like the job name, account, partition, nodes, tasks per node, CPUs per task, and the job's runtime. 

It also defines a `SPACK_INSTANCE_DIR`, which is the location of the SPACK instance used to install packages.  The script configures and lists the SPACK settings for compilers, config options, mirrors, modules, packages, repos, and upstreams. 

It uses `spack spec` to check for a valid concrete version of the specified package, then utilizes `spack install` to install the package with specific parameters like the number of jobs and the `--fail-fast` and `--yes-to-all` flags. It then refreshes the LMOD module environment with the newly installed package using `spack module lmod refresh`. Finally, it submits another job using `sbatch` that depends on the current job and executes a script named `gh@2.0.0.sh`.
